summary: Expressed solidarity with families who lost loved ones on 9/11 and committed to supporting those families, ensuring they receive the resources they need. Additionally, expressed sympathy and support for families of victims and hostages from the October 7th attack and committed to doing everything possible to help bring remaining hostages home. Also supported enforcement actions to keep illegal, addictive e-cigarette products out of the hands of children and prevent youth nicotine addiction. Supported keeping SBA Microloan program functioning during shutdowns, noting it provides short-term loans to small businesses and certain non-profit childcare centers, thereby protecting childcare providers and families. Introduced the Expanding Child Care Access Act to provide a refundable tax credit of up to $5,000 to cover startup expenses for new family child care (in-home daycare) businesses once they receive state license/registration, aiming to grow affordable, locally based child care options that serve families with nontraditional hours, rural families, those with young children, and limited English proficiency; emphasized supporting providers (majority women- and women-of-color-owned), expanding access, and helping parents remain in the workforce. Secured community funding for recreational and park improvements, soccer field and municipal recreation lighting upgrades, and community center and library improvements to expand safe places for children and families to learn and play. Cosponsored the Tobacco TRACE Act to protect youth from unlawful e-cigarettes and other illicit tobacco products by requiring secure, trackable codes and reducing the availability of harmful products to middle and high school students. The new senior staff team includes Laney Oâ€™Shea, who led work on child care policy, indicating continued legislative focus and in-office expertise on expanding child care access and supports for families. In a March 4, 2025 statement responding to the President's joint address, he also invoked the need to "build a brighter future for our children" as part of his call to support middle-class families and pursue policies that benefit kids across the district. Upon being sworn in to represent New Jersey's 3rd District, he reaffirmed a commitment to uplifting the economy and ensuring working families in his district and across the country can thrive, reinforcing his focus on policies that benefit parents and children. The January 3, 2025 "Newest Members of Congress" release recorded his swearing-in and reiterated these family-focused commitments.

Gill supports youth pathways to public service and military careers, overseeing an advisory board that evaluates and recommends high school and college applicants from his district for service academy nominations and highlighting the opportunity for young people to serve upon graduation. He also publicly recognizes and encourages young innovators in his district through programs like the Congressional App Challenge, endorsing STEM and computer science education for middle and high school students. In a March 2025 press release he praised President Trump's leadership as 'renewing the American Dream' and emphasized that the administration is 'defending our families' from what he called Democrat-caused 'destruction.' In September 2025 he sponsored and saw House passage of the DC Juvenile Sentencing Reform Act, supporting lowering the age for transfer to adult court from 16 to 14 for certain violent offenses so that serious juvenile offenders face adult criminal accountability; he argued the change would increase prosecutable cases and protect public safety. He additionally hosts the annual Congressional Art Competition for TX-26 high school students, celebrating youth creativity, arts education, and community engagement by displaying winning student artwork in the U.S. Capitol and his district offices. In March 2025 he also introduced a bill to direct the USPS to create a unique ZIP code for Northlake, arguing the designation would strengthen community identity, reduce mailing and boundary confusion, protect local sales tax revenue, and benefit families living in the fast-growing town. In November 2025 he emphasized constituent impacts during the 43-day federal government shutdown, saying families 'suffered' and paychecks lapsed, kept his district offices open to serve constituents during the lapse, and requested that his own paycheck be withheld for the duration of the shutdown.

Advocates for family literacy programs and targeted support for children in high-poverty schools who disproportionately lack access to school libraries and librarians, emphasizing literacy as a gateway to opportunity. Has championed early childhood access by launching a county's first free pre-school program and supports services that help working families and children succeed. Cosponsored the Child Care for Working Families Act to expand childcare, provide universal pre-K, cap childcare costs, and advance paid family and medical leave and other family supports.

Highlighted President Jimmy Carter's post-presidential work with Habitat for Humanity, noting Carter helped build homes for Georgians in need in LaGrange, reflecting attention to community housing assistance and volunteer-driven support for families. Also launched the 2025 Congressional Art Competition inviting high school students to participate, reflecting attention to youth opportunities and arts programming. Additionally promotes career and technical education for high school students (toured CTE labs and convened a roundtable with the Secretary of Education) to prepare youth for careers and expand opportunities for students in his district. Hosted the Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Scott Turner at church services in Zebulon, using Cabinet visits to highlight faith-based community engagement and local programs that affect families and neighborhoods.
